  ## Plan Overview
  
A Data Management Plan created using DMPTool
Title: The governance of the Waimiri Atroari Indigenous Territory: environmental justice and community
management
Creator: Silvia De melo futada
Affiliation: University of Florida (ufl.edu)
Contributor: Emilio Bruna
Funder: National Science Foundation (nsf.gov)
Template: NSF-GEN: Generic

Project abstract:
This Ph.D. research from Silvia de Melo Futada (sfutada@ufl.edu) addresses environmental governance and justice
regarding indigenous knowledge and management in the Brazilian Amazonia, specifically the Waimiri Atroari
Indigenous Territory. The Waimiri-Atroari (WA) - a Carib-speaking indigenous society — were betrayed, hunted,
and nearly exterminated: decreasing from an estimated population of 3,000 in the 1900s to 374 people in the 1980s.
Territorial reductions and national infrastructure projects were constructed therein, flooding entire villages.
Nowadays, after 35 years, the WA society went from an almost extinct society, persecuted in their territory, to a
flourishing population in some of the best- conserved Indigenous Lands (IL) in Brazil. The community established a
territorial protection program that includes monitoring wildlife-vehicle collisions and a health and educational
system in their language, with over 2,400 individuals. This research provides a baseline understanding of this
unique case of IL governance based on community management and indigenous strategies, providing a model of
governance policies in an intercultural context. It also aims to develop a codesign of the research process with the
WA society. I will address the research questions through interdisciplinary mixed-method research.

Start date: 04-30-2023
End date: 07-30-2026
Last modified: 03-18-2023
